The Committee, subject to the Board's approval shall:
Evaluate, examine, and determine the qualifications for applicants for registration as a veterinary technician;
Recommend to the Board the subject, scope, form, date, time, and location for each examination;
Establish continuing education requirements for veterinary technicians;
Define the duties and responsibilities of registered veterinary technicians;
Recommend to the Board reasonable rules and regulations to carry out the provisions of this section; and
Generally assist the Board in registering and regulating veterinary technicians.

The Board shall register any applicant who:
Meets the requirements of this section;
Meets the Board's educational requirements;
Passes a Board approved examination;
Is of good moral character; and
Is at least 18 years old.

The Board shall renew the registration of any applicant for an additional 3-year term if the applicant:
Submits a renewal application on the form that the Board requires;
Pays to the Board a renewal fee set by the Board;
Complies with the Board's continuing education requirements; and
Otherwise is entitled to be registered.

In accordance with the hearing provisions of § 2-311 of this subtitle, the Board may refuse to register an applicant, suspend or revoke the registration, or reprimand and censure, or place on probation any veterinary technician, if the veterinary technician:
Practices veterinary medicine except as permitted under this subtitle;
Fraudulently or deceptively obtains a registration;
Is professionally, physically, or mentally incompetent;
Is convicted of a felony or a crime involving moral turpitude;
Is convicted of a violation of any federal or State law relating to narcotic drugs;
Is grossly negligent or deliberately cruel to an animal;
Violates any provisions of this subtitle; or
Is determined by the Board to be incompetent as a veterinary technician.
